>>38015083
That's a pretty lame excuse. A story can be a complete meme without being a poorly written story. In fact, a well panned and written story would be a significantly better meme. You remember when "read the first letter of every line" was a big thing? Imagine that sort of thing but for a whole story. A huge reveal that, instead of being a sad or shocking moment, is one of hilarity. Think the biggest and best plot twists in stories, the ones that completely define the work. They are meticulously laid out with painstaking effort to intertwine and foreshadow them. This is part of what gives them their enormous payoff. Wouldn't something like that for comedy be incredible to have?
Also, writing it from one part to another completely at random makes it very dream-like in a bad way. It sounds great in your head, but it's terrible to actually read due to its incoherence.

Anonymous Mon 19 Apr 2021 03:50:24 No.38017391 Report
Quoted By: >>38018164
>>38016854
The dialogue itself just comes off as unnatural and needs revision to work out awkward delivery and redundancy. I'm pulling out of the most recent updates but these issues exist across the story.
>"Yeah, who would've thought a Stalker, Arms dealer, And a detective would become best friends." Judith says
Inconsistency in use of indefinite article (a/an), and also doesn't really add anything to the previous lines, which discuss the same thing.
>"It was most romantic! We saw the movie version of 'Deer to me' We even had our first kiss afterward!" Renée says in an excited tone
Tacking the first kiss part on at the end like an afterthought feels wrong because it's something that most girls would either lead with or build up to when talking about their love life. 'Says in an excited tone' is poor and should be replaced with a single word that better qualifies the delivery. I would opt for 'Renee squeals' but a number of options can work here.
Dialogue can be tricky because people talk in different ways, but it helps to imagine how your characters deliver their lines within a scene, and do your best to act it out irl. If something sounds wrong to you, modify it until it sounds right. If you write dialogue well enough, it should be obvious who's speaking, what's being talked about, and how the speaker feels about the subject with minimal use of descriptors or body language.
You use too many proper nouns, and should replace them with pronouns in some places and with some kind of descriptor in others. Occupation or physical descriptors are ideal. For Amelia, you can refer to her by not only her name, but also as 'Detective/Officer Ortmeyer', 'the officer', 'the mouse/mouse-woman/she-mouse' and I'm sure plenty more. Some of these may be more appropriate in one scene than others, so you need to use your judgement for where it actively distinguishes the characters.

Anonymous Mon 19 Apr 2021 03:58:36 No.38017606 Report

>>38017167
>anthros are aliens? By their science, we shouldn't exist
That's kind of a contradiction right there. If they are anthro in form, then humans are just a variant of the anthro form factor. It might express itself oddly (how can they not have fur?), but "shouldn't exist" is a bit of a stretch for a star-faring civilization.

In a bigger picture, certainly we can imagine a star-faring civilization populated primarily by anthro species, and discovering humans is a freaky oddity. Not entirely sure what would be so weird or unique that they would be shocked into re-evaluating their fundamental science. Just loo at the levels of imagination we humans are at today, the fantastical creatures we speculate about and how they could be biologically possible. And, we are hardly a star-faring race, we're very primitive by that metric.

So, yeah. Humans are surprising, something/somehow unique. Possibly the fact that we are the only sapient species to evolve on our planet (which is a theme with a lot of speculation to it even by ourselves). Not sure what would make us so "valuable" as to cause an interstellar race/conflict to secure Earth. I'd have to think about that a lot before I was comfortable in a good enough reason.

One direction I'd speculate might be that we show far more potential than most species. It isn't what we are so much as how advanced we are relative to our situation and the point in our evolutionary timeline we're at. That might be unusual enough to cause interstellar excitement. A pre-space traveling civilization comprised of a mono-species evolution that has developed surprisingly advanced science without somehow cracking the light speed barrier. A bizarre curiosity that may have a lot to offer ... once they are made less dangerous.

I was just thinking out loud, too, anon. Based upon the info available to me.

That's an interesting twist I hadn't considered, about non-mammal anthros discovering an unexpected, highly improbable mammalian anthro species. I think it still falls short of the "shouldn't exist" standard, but much less so than I was originally thinking. It could be very startling and cause a deep re-examination of their biological and xenobiology sciences. If it is a galactic-wide civilization with hundred sof species, it becomes less probable, but if it's confined to this arm of he galaxy and they've only encountered maybe a dozen saurean-based species, plus maybe an insectiod hive mind, four hundred or a thousand years into their space exploration they run across a mammalian anthro that was a very distant hypothetical and it could make for a quite plausible core plotline.

You should familiarize yourself with two major Star Trek plots. From the original series and then re-explored slightly in Enterprise, there is the Gorn. They are a saurian-based anthro, very rare in the Trek universe. Imagining Star Trek where all species are largely saurian and a few other oddities, then suddenly they run across a crazy, dangerous species of mammals is probably a thought exercise that will help you somewhat.

Then, a nearly stand-alone episode of Voyager has them discovering a race of evolved dinosaurs that are very slightly genetically related to humans. Turns out that a sapient dinosaur species escaped Earth just before the great dinosaur extinction 65 million years ago. Both our Federation humans and the race of dinosaurs have a very difficult time imagining even the possibility that the other might exist. The dinos in that episode are far more advanced than humans technologically. Again, interesting thought project to watch that episode and imagine a galaxy of dinos that unexpectedly run across barely hypothetical mammal sapients.
